</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B14CF4DCA911BF753E281CF1C533DBCD" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="ED1E25464E6F9B100AF4061A2C43B860" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4BB3181084119828499CBDFFF4FD137A" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName id="38977ABB4427D6DD2986AEBEC2EEAB36" authorityName="C. - I Peng" authorityYear="2020" class="Cephalopoda" family="Graphoceratidae" genus="Ludwigia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ludwigia glandulosa subsp. brachycarpa" order="Ammonoidea" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subSpecies" species="glandulosa" subSpecies="brachycarpa">Ludwigia glandulosa subsp. brachycarpa</taxonomicName>
differs from typical 
<taxonomicName id="440F0AA7A3483536C0D64F4A44DCB576" genus="L." lsidName="L. glandulosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="glandulosa">
<emphasis id="E896B48FFE6245D24CB470C6676B5A45" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">L. glandulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its smaller stature, 10-55(-90) cm (vs. (20-)40-80(-100) cm); narrower leaf blades, 0.3-0.5(-1) cm (vs. 0.3-2.1 cm); shorter sepals, 1.1-1.9 mm (vs. 1.3-2.3 cm); smaller capsules, 2-5 
<normalizedToken id="B247957858DA19E2512C185F1C34DFF4" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.3-2 mm (vs. (4-)5-8(-9) 
<normalizedToken id="14645515E5BE6C94D035E7D078B79C2D" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.6-2(-3) mm); and seed surface cells elongate transversely to length (vs. surface cells elongate parallel to length).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B2F4C7A16ADCF5DB346D63EFC4286101" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="type material">
<paragraph id="3E0BBDC16BAF3B92EF18CE39F841D6F3" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Type material.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC7CDF7DC5C668CD2BD715CCF5D8963C" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis id="13AE31E0F540BD3EA99A45556E99362E" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">USA, Louisiana</emphasis>
, Cameron Parish, 3.2 km W of junction State Highways 82 and 27, 
<geoCoordinate id="E553D9082B792234DBF871CD1BC10A30" degrees="29" direction="north" minutes="48.62" orientation="latitude" precision="9" value="29.810333">29°48.62'N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="105018FD379894582142F7BA7EF96AC5" degrees="93" direction="west" minutes="08.25" orientation="longitude" precision="9" value="-93.1375">93°08.25'W</geoCoordinate>
, 1 m, 16 August 1980, 
<emphasis id="38947E5603FBE1589898A7986224EB75" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">C.-I Peng, W. Peng and J. Chen 4367</emphasis>
(holotype: MO 2806683); see fig. 42 in 
<bibRefCitation id="9F47E99527BEC78FF28171CC2F73E4E9" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2399348" author="Peng, CI" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="221 - 302" refId="B12" refString="Peng, CI, 1989. The systematics and evolution of Ludwigia sect. Microcarpium (Onagraceae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76 (1): 221 - 302, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2399348" title="The systematics and evolution of Ludwigia sect. Microcarpium (Onagraceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2399348" volume="76" year="1989">Peng (1989)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3AA4409AB2C39E49FEE81FE7796A1991" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="description">
<paragraph id="C9E95BF4C2879324F01414EFD5057E9C" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB765DD0E43F42C39026D7910AAFE6FA" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis id="1A22E1D8F905F1199D529B55F2692DF3" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Stems</emphasis>
rarely reddish green, 10-55(-90) cm. 
<emphasis id="2F5DCD75D5FC235F3CBB3C9C02D2E373" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Leaves</emphasis>
: petiole 0-1 cm, blades linear-elliptic to linear, sometimes very narrowly elliptic, those on main axis 3-5(-7) 
<normalizedToken id="010A17572458D7A7F2811DBF5968E485" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.3-0.5(-1) cm, those on branches 0.8-3.6 
<normalizedToken id="AAB0C1B8D1576CF2ACA99E850C60611A" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.2-0.3(-0.8) cm. 
<emphasis id="6C71078FC89D05707DC6531F5B73EE55" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Inflorescences</emphasis>
: bracteoles attached at base of ovary, 0.4-0.8 
<normalizedToken id="E3BF1B603DF60F39CECF65C9338B3EE1" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.1-0.2 mm. 
<emphasis id="838AEC924633B8CB51042F51A68B5D51" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Flowers</emphasis>
: sepals 1.1-1.9 
<normalizedToken id="000D501623895B60AEDABDCECF96FA42" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-1.8 mm, apex acute or short-acuminate; nectary disc obscurely, minutely papillose; style 0.4-0.8 mm, stigma 0.2-0.3 mm diam. 
<emphasis id="165CE2A363ABB58D50C9BF59709170C4" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Capsules</emphasis>
obscurely 4-angled, 2-5 
<normalizedToken id="E630FD89D02FD298877BBAE7EE4AA1D3" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.3-2 mm, pedicel 0-0.2 mm. 
<emphasis id="0398CD9D28016C17E75C7FCD98811B23" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Seeds</emphasis>
0.6-0.8 
<normalizedToken id="278AEE58FCC3EFFDBDDBAB28EC882927" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.3-0.4 mm, surface cells elongate transversely to seed length. 
<emphasis id="3AA1C60A989AE4D19BA66AB6B453CCC9" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Chromosome number</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis id="2E8EB808C0730AF82D6AD9B7BA920815" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">n</emphasis>
= 16.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="99FA5CD5FD99C3FD3EC334AD0C60B070" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="4164CF2C33408F8669FD907482177ADE" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C57C2137A076EF3DD1E6415D3450738B" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Flowering and fruiting April to November.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C0A1D44ECD6C912AE2846426E8EB9A34" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="F5283042B24004B37C21410E187F6239" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4C02E252B1FB7656ECB43567B34BFD84" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
The subspecific epithet ' 
<emphasis id="FCB161340BDB06AC8B7BCDA207D59473" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">brachycarpum</emphasis>
' refers to the short capsules.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BF8C16DEC750A662971A312E73CDF600" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="3BA3FBF5894F1E250A95209F55E69CE0" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F9E3240C33D80EC279E58E030DB11F62" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName id="0739B522AAD042E7AB194655B4B44123" authorityName="C. - I Peng" authorityYear="2020" class="Cephalopoda" family="Graphoceratidae" genus="Ludwigia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ludwigia glandulosa subsp. brachycarpa" order="Ammonoidea" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subSpecies" species="glandulosa" subSpecies="brachycarpa">Ludwigia glandulosa subsp. brachycarpa</taxonomicName>
is endemic to the US Gulf Coast from southwestern Louisiana to Nueces County, Texas, and more sporadically northward in eastern Texas to south-central Oklahoma. This distribution is at the extreme southwestern edge of that for subsp. 
<taxonomicName id="4B3C08D860908F8CB9CB6A74BE112D87" class="Cephalopoda" family="Graphoceratidae" genus="Ludwigia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="subsp. glandulosum" order="Ammonoidea" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subSpecies" species="glandulosa" subSpecies="glandulosum">glandulosum</taxonomicName>
, which grows from Texas and Oklahoma east to Virginia and Florida and north to southern Missouri, Illinois, and Indiana (
<bibRefCitation id="07324A68045238986CEB996207445BA3" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2399348" author="Peng, CI" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="221 - 302" refId="B12" refString="Peng, CI, 1989. The systematics and evolution of Ludwigia sect. Microcarpium (Onagraceae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76 (1): 221 - 302, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2399348" title="The systematics and evolution of Ludwigia sect. Microcarpium (Onagraceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2399348" volume="76" year="1989">Peng 1989</bibRefCitation>
). Although they overlap in part, the two taxa are only rarely locally sympatric. 
<taxonomicName id="D1963E6CFE7554266740FD9FBF42ABD3" authorityName="C. - I Peng" authorityYear="2020" class="Cephalopoda" family="Graphoceratidae" genus="Ludwigia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ludwigia glandulosa subsp. brachycarpa" order="Ammonoidea" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subSpecies" species="glandulosa" subSpecies="brachycarpa">Ludwigia glandulosa subsp. brachycarpa</taxonomicName>
grows in ditches, low meadows, coastal prairies, seeps in sandy woods, moist sinkholes in granite outcrops, old clay fields at an elevation of 0-200 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C0B70236E5F46206F9583338F68EA7C6" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="new combinations">
<paragraph id="8B1AF75FC36B668B31D34170CD7A54F5" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">New combinations</paragraph>
<paragraph id="639C352F8A95873EB92C272DE8240A63" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName id="FED47B098D5181FD5061625F9B5A83B7" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Epilobium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Epilobium" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="BD25D23C2D8AD52D8BA1C0A68A9E7716" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Epilobium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. is the largest genus in the family 
<taxonomicName id="83D6073610B3EB865726647C0A3E55EB" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Epilobium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Onagraceae</taxonomicName>
; its 165 species are widely distributed in cool or cold regions of the world, with a center of diversity in western North America (
<bibRefCitation id="E3B5F8F029743FAF500053551415F3B7" author="Wagner, WL" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany Monographs" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="1 - 240" refId="B16" refString="Wagner, WL, Hoch, PC, Raven, PH, 2007. Revised classification of the Onagraceae. Systematic Botany Monographs 83: 1 - 240" title="Revised classification of the Onagraceae." volume="83" year="2007">Wagner et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
). A group of annual species with affinities to 
<taxonomicName id="469C3E5DA7D42908CCBCB07C6751D719" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Epilobium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Epilobium" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E7A857E65E0A63E8DB4D504A2E714312" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Epilobium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but considered distinct because they lack seed comas was historically segregated as 
<taxonomicName id="1B30E5BC6FC577DD8435B4F3C44FDCD7" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Boisduvalia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Boisduvalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6498B99A2DD9621404F3FC2222B6AA58" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Boisduvalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Spach (
<bibRefCitation id="85C2777DB08CB7302F9F13AEC8FA502A" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2395311" author="Raven, PH" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="326 - 340" refId="B14" refString="Raven, PH, 1976. Generic and sectional delimitation in Onagraceae, tribe Epilobieae. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 63 (2): 326 - 340, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2395311" title="Generic and sectional delimitation in Onagraceae, tribe Epilobieae." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2395311" volume="63" year="1976">Raven 1976</bibRefCitation>
). However, molecular and other evidence (
<bibRefCitation id="86CEB1FDD985FFF2ECA78E170F531974" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.part.16727" author="Hoch, PC" journalOrPublisher="Phytologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="456 - 459" refId="B5" refString="Hoch, PC, Raven, PH, 1992. Boisduvalia, a coma-less Epilobium (Onagraceae). Phytologia 73: 456 - 459, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.part.16727" title="Boisduvalia, a coma-less Epilobium (Onagraceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.part.16727" volume="73" year="1992">Hoch and Raven 1992</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="6EDD26DC2189BA8D6E1457688BA0D370" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2419763" author="Baum, DA" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="363 - 388" refId="B1" refString="Baum, DA, Sytsma, KJ, Hoch, PC, 1994. The phylogeny of Epilobium (Onagraceae) based on nuclear ribosomal DNA sequences. Systematic Botany 19 (3): 363 - 388, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2419763" title="The phylogeny of Epilobium (Onagraceae) based on nuclear ribosomal DNA sequences." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2419763" volume="19" year="1994">Baum et al. 1994</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="6F1C44372CCB7FA7BBE1642B71BB7129" author="Wagner, WL" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany Monographs" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="1 - 240" refId="B16" refString="Wagner, WL, Hoch, PC, Raven, PH, 2007. Revised classification of the Onagraceae. Systematic Botany Monographs 83: 1 - 240" title="Revised classification of the Onagraceae." volume="83" year="2007">Wagner et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
) unequivocally place 
<taxonomicName id="850C1E3BB9ADAAD4DDA8DA5D72E712C4" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Boisduvalia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Boisduvalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33338D4D6E7C4341EB91BA9320A8CC85" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Boisduvalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
within 
<taxonomicName id="E8EC6EF686E31133220B886EC50041AA" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Epilobium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Epilobium" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="65D4B46B51F2EDD9D2E6E08C83F9F0E4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Epilobium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as two non-monophyletic sections. 
<taxonomicName id="77DE74D999E99291849FCDA2A91E2705" authorityName="Hoch &amp; Gandhi" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Hoch &amp; Gandhi" baseAuthorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Epilobium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Epilobium subsp. sect." order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Epilobiopsis" species="glandulosa" subSpecies="sect.">Epilobium sect. Epilobiopsis</taxonomicName>
(Spegazzini) Lievens, Hoch &amp; PH Raven is a group of two species characterized by tough, tardily dehiscing capsules, seeds in two rows per locule, and a chromosome number of 
<emphasis id="94BC496E5655AFAAAAAA961D768743B2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">n</emphasis>
= 15; and 
<taxonomicName id="0CCB95ACFA3424A49B131FA775A678DB" genus="E." lsidName="E. subsp. sect." pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="section" section="Boisduvalia" species="glandulosa" subSpecies="sect.">E. sect. Boisduvalia</taxonomicName>
(Spach) Hoch &amp; P. H. Raven is a group of four species characterized by friable, readily dehiscing capsules, seeds in one row per locule, and chromosome numbers of 
<emphasis id="AEF8C404D80A8E74928C7A497B2BD228" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">n</emphasis>
= 9, 10, 19. In naming this latter section, however, we overlooked an earlier name at the sectional level, one of two proposed for this group by 
<bibRefCitation id="D1CD161529C053AED249CCFAF8BA57CB" author="Fischer, FEL" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany Monographs" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" refId="B3" refString="Fischer, FEL, Meyer, CA, 1836. Index Seminum [St. Petersburg (Petropolitanus)] 2: 45." title="Index Seminum [St. Petersburg (Petropolitanus)] 2: 45." year="1836">Fischer and Meyer (1836)</bibRefCitation>
, who treated the group as part of 
<taxonomicName id="995A4AB30FCBE37DB54707A67D5844BF" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Oenothera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Oenothera" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B70642E046E60B569E06C5F9F816E1D7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Oenothera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. due to the absence of seed comas. Therefore, a new combination is required.
</paragraph>
